Alamosaurus.etymology: (Named for the Alamo area of New Mexico)

Albertosaurus.etymology: (Named for the Canadian province of Alberta)

Amphicoelias.etymology: (Greek: amphi 'both sides' + koilos 'hollow', referring to its vertebrae)

Ankylosaurus.etymology: (Greek: ankylos 'bent' or 'fused', referring to its fused bones)

Apatosaurus.etymology: (Greek: apatos 'deceptive', due to a misplaced vertebra)

Arandaspis.etymology: (Named after the Aranda aboriginal people + Greek: aspis 'shield')

Archaeothyris.etymology: (Greek: archaios 'ancient' + thyris 'window', referring to a hole in the skull)

Ardeosaurus.etymology: (Named for the Solnhofen area of Ardèche)

Argentinosaurus.etymology: (Named for the country where it was found)

Askeptosaurus.etymology: (Greek: askeptos 'unseen' or 'not to be examined' + sauros 'lizard')

Bactrosaurus.etymology: (Greek: baktron 'club' or 'staff', referring to its neural spines)

Barapasaurus.etymology: (Local Indian dialect for 'big leg' + Greek: sauros 'lizard')

Bernissartia.etymology: (Named after Bernissart, Belgium, where it was found)

Bothriolepis.etymology: (Greek: bothrion 'pit' + lepis 'scale', referring to depressions on its armor)

Brachiosaurus.etymology: (Greek: brachion 'arm', as its forelegs were longer than its hindlegs)

Camarasaurus.etymology: (Greek: kamara 'chamber', referring to hollow spaces in its vertebrae)

Canobius.etymology: (Named for Ken, a fishing area, and Greek: bios 'life')

Casea.etymology: (Named for American paleontologist E. C. Case)

Ceratosaurus.etymology: (Greek: keras 'horn', referring to its nasal horn)

Chasmosaurus.etymology: (Greek: chasma 'opening', referring to large fenestrae in its frill)

Claudiosaurus.etymology: (Named for a Dr. Claude + Greek: sauros 'lizard')

Coelophysis.etymology: (Greek: koilos 'hollow' + physis 'form', referring to hollow bones)

Deltoptychius.etymology: (Greek: delta 'delta' + ptychos 'fold', referring to fin folds)

Diatryma.etymology: (Greek: diatryma 'hole, perforation', referring to skull opening)

Dicraeosaurus.etymology: (Greek: dikraios 'two-forked', referring to its neural spines)

Diplocaulus.etymology: (Greek: diploos 'double' + kaulos 'stalk', referring to its head shape)

Diplodocus.etymology: (Greek: diploos 'double' + dokos 'beam', referring to its double-beamed tail vertebrae)

Dipterus.etymology: (Greek: di 'two' + pteron 'wing', referring to its fins)

Dodo.etymology: (Possibly from Dutch: dodoor 'sluggard' or Portuguese: doudo 'crazy')

Dromiceiomimus.etymology: (Greek: dromeios 'running' + mimos 'mimic', referring to the emu-like appearance)

Dryosaurus.etymology: (Greek: dryos 'oak', referring to a forest habitat)

Dsungaripterus.etymology: (Named for the Dzungaria basin in China + Greek: pteron 'wing')

Dunkleosteus.etymology: (Named for paleontologist David Dunkle + Greek: osteon 'bone')

Edaphosaurus.etymology: (Greek: edaphos 'ground/pavement', referring to its jaw structure)

Edmontosaurus.etymology: (Named for the Edmonton Formation in Canada)

Elasmosaurus.etymology: (Greek: elasmos 'plate, thin metal', referring to its thin vertebral plates)

Elginia.etymology: (Named after the town of Elgin, Scotland)

Emeus.etymology: (From a native name for the Australian Emu)

Euparkeria.etymology: (Greek: eu 'true' + Named for Mr. W. G. Parker)

Great Auk.etymology: (No scientific translation; 'Auk' is from Old Norse)

Greererpeton.etymology: (Named for Greer, West Virginia + Greek: herpeton 'crawler')

Haramiyia.etymology: (Named for the area in Jordan where found, Haramiya)

Hovasaurus.etymology: (Named after the Hova people of Madagascar)

Iguanodon.etymology: (Named for its resemblance to the teeth of an Iguana)

Jamoytius.etymology: (Named for an island in Scotland, Isle of Jamoy)

Kannemeyeria.etymology: (Named for a collector, D. R. Kannemeyer)

Kritosaurus.etymology: (Greek: kritos 'separated', referring to its oddly preserved skull)

Lystrosaurus.etymology: (Greek: lystron 'shovel', referring to its skull shape)

Mamenchisaurus.etymology: (Named for the Mamenchi Ferry crossing in China)

Milleretta.etymology: (Named for the Scottish geologist Hugh Miller)

Mixosaurus.etymology: (Greek: mixis 'mixing', as it had mixed features)

Mosasaurus.etymology: (Named for the Meuse River in the Netherlands)

Muraenosaurus.etymology: (Named for the Moray Firth in Scotland)

Mussaurus.etymology: (Latin: mus 'mouse', as the first specimen was a small juvenile)

Nodosaurus.etymology: (Latin: nodus 'knot' or 'swelling', referring to its armor nodes)

Ophthalmosaurus.etymology: (Greek: ophthalmos 'eye', referring to its large eye sockets)

Plesiosaurus.etymology: (Greek: plesios 'near', thought to be closer to crocodiles than ichthyosaurs)

Pliosaurus.etymology: (Greek: pleiōn 'more', implying it was more evolved than Plesiosaurus)

Quetzalcoatlus.etymology: (Named after the Aztec feathered serpent god Quetzalcoatl)

Shonisaurus.etymology: (Named for the Shoshone Mountains in Nevada)

Spinosaurus.etymology: (Latin: spina 'spine' + Greek: sauros 'lizard', referring to its neural spines)

Stegosaurus.etymology: (Greek: stegē 'roof/plate' + sauros 'lizard', referring to its back plates)

Talarurus.etymology: (Greek: talaron 'wicker basket', referring to its tail club)

Tenontosaurus.etymology: (Greek: tenōn 'sinew', referring to its ossified tendons)

Ticinosuchus.etymology: (Named for the Ticino River in Switzerland)

Torosaurus.etymology: (Greek: toros 'perforated/pierced' + sauros 'lizard', referring to holes in its frill)

Triadobatrachus.etymology: (Named for the Triassic period + Greek: batrachos 'frog')

Tuojiangosaurus.etymology: (Named for the Tuo River in China)

Varanosaurus.etymology: (Named for its resemblance to modern monitor lizards, *Varanus*)

Wuerhosaurus.etymology: (Named for the Wuerho area in China)

Zalambdalestes.etymology: (Referring to the shape of one of its teeth)
